This paper deals with self-stabilizing algorithms for wireless ad hoc networks, which are typically studied in the computer networks (cs.NI) and distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-categories. The use of TDMA algorithms involves time and scheduling, which are also relevant to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The problem of collision-free communication involves graph coloring and connectivity, which are relevant to the discrete mathematics (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the use of self-stabilizing algorithms involves fault tolerance and system dynamics, which are relevant to the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category.
